Text.Value: You have done what we feared was impossible. You have released me from a century of sorrow.
We need to leave. Lady Shar won't stand for us to be here - not after what we did.
You have done what we feared was impossible. You have released me from a century of sorrow.
To kill Ketheric Thorm.

EditorData.NodeContext: Her last line before flying off. Determination and vigour.

Text.Value: *It is time to leave this place, and see what chaos you have unleashed upon Moonrise Towers.*
Your power is great. So too must be your weapon. You must choose what you will wield. And the Moonmaiden will provide. Thus I have said; thus will it be so.
We're going to kill Ketheric Thorm.

EditorData.NodeContext: Her last line before flying off. Determination and vigour.

Text.Value: Let's get out of here, please. Whatever's coming, I don't want to be in the heart of the Shadowfell when it finds me.
For my weapon? Naturally.
If Shar is angry, she's being remarkably quiet about it.
Ho! And it shall be yours. And then?
Dark Lady be merciful... What have I done?
You have done me an incredible service. The Moonmaiden has blessed you in kind.

All right, let's get out of here.
What just happened?
*Yet no pain, no recrimination. Only silence. And somehow, this strikes you as worse.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Shadowheart looks at her hand with some surprise and fear.

Text.Value: The Nightsong will be headed for Moonrise Towers. We'd better get there, and see what she's unleashed against Ketheric Thorm.
For my weapon? Absolutely.

It is your turn, my friend.
It is your turn.
Are you ready?
Are you ready?
That's what frightens me. She must be angry, yet I don't feel it, or hear it... There's only silence.

Text.Value: I'm not sure there's a place that's far enough away for me to go. Lady Shar must be angry... but there's only silence.

Text.Value: You have injured me, soldier. But you have given me a great gift, too.
*A shudder of fear runs through you. Lady Shar asked you to prove yourself - and you failed.*

Ready for what?
And now? Now, Ketheric Thorm must die.

Text.Value:
Our Lady of Silver. Hear me!
She Who Guides, the Moonmaiden Selûne -
MOTHER OF THE SO-CALLED NIGHTSONG.
THE NIGHTSONG IS NO MORE!

EditorData.AnimationTags: [GOLD] NS: steps from the cage and drops to the ground, finally free of her 100 year imprisonment. She begins pounding her fist in a rhythm and slowly rises to her feet in triumph.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
She kneels, head down, allowing the player to lay a hand upon her shoulder. As the hand makes contact, the hands appear upon her again - they glow and burs/ fade awayt. She steps forward nervously and stumbles, not having been free in a century and momentarily dizzied by the prospect of it. She catches herself on hand and knees, her head hanging. She begins to beat the ground with a fist in a slow, powerful rhythm. Then, she begins to hum an ancient, almost Gregorian chant. As she hums, the sound of it echoing through the Shadowfell builds and morphs into a chorus humming in harmony with her. She raises herself to her feet, but the rhythm continues, as does the song, independently of her.

Text.Value: I am resplendent.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [GOLD] NS: lifts into the air as a Moonbeam shines upon her like a spotlight. Within the light she transforms into her angelic form and basks in her own glory for a moment before settling back down to speak with the Player.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
A moonbeam lands on Nightsong, like a spotlight. She begins to glow as the music swells and reaches its climax.
Within the moonbeam, she transforms. Her wounds heal, and her rusted, dirty armour and torn clothes begin to mend.
The ragged, violently marred costume she was wearing is replaced, piece by piece, with the shining armour of a paladin of Selune.The spotlight on Nightsong fades. She is renewed, beautiful, powerful.
EditorData.NodeContext: With joy and gratitiude. Not ego, but fact.
EditorData.SFXTags: Nightsong descends back in front of the player in her gleaming armor and great sword
